def: The malicious burning of a dwelling house or outhouse ofanother man, which by the common law is felony; the malicious andvoluntary firing of a building or ship. Wharton.
Not sincere or pure; insincere. [Obs.] Dryden.-- Un`sin*cere"ness, n. [Obs.]
A cornice, or series of moldings, on the top of the base of apedestal, podium, etc. See Illust. of Column.
Being before, or in front. [R.] J. Fleming.
The act or process of ascertaining the proportion of aparticular metal in an ore or alloy; especially, the determination ofthe proportion of gold or silver in bullion or coin.
Power; force; energy; spirit; activity; vigor. [Colloq.]
A priest who becomes a martyr.

A very large lizard (Varanaus salvator) native of India. Itfrequents the borders of streams and swims actively. It becomes fiveor six feet long. Called also two-banded monitor, and kabaragoya. Thename is also applied to other aquatic monitors.
An ear tuft of feathers, as in the horned owls.
A form of melodiograph applied to a piano.
One skilled in ornithology; a student of ornithology; one whodescribes birds.
